  "Question": "<p>My PreCalculus teacher recently reviewed the properties of limits with us before our test and stated that <em>any real number divided by infinity equals zero</em>. This got me thinking and I asked them whether a <strong>complex number</strong> (i.e. <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_236\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"3+2i\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mn>3</mn> <mo>+</mo> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>i</mi> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span> or <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_237\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"-4i\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mrow> <mn>4</mn> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>i</mi> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span>) <strong>divided by infinity would equal zero</strong>. </p> <p>This completely stumped them and I was unable to get an answer. After doing some theoretical calculation, knowing that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_238\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"i=\\sqrt{-1}\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>i</mi> <mo>=</mo> <msqrt> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </msqrt> </mrow> </math></span>, I calculated that a complex number such as <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_239\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\frac{5i}{\\infty}=0\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>5</mn> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>i</mi> </mrow> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u221e</mi> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> </math></span> since  <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_240\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\frac{5}{\\infty}\\cdot\\frac{\\sqrt{-1}}{\\infty}=0\\cdot 0=0,\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <mrow> <mfrac> <mn>5</mn> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u221e</mi> </mfrac> <mo>\u22c5</mo> <mfrac> <msqrt> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </msqrt> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u221e</mi> </mfrac> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mrow> <mn>0</mn> <mo>\u22c5</mo> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> <mo>,</mo> </mrow> </math></span>  using properties utilized with real numbers that would state that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_241\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\frac{5x}{\\infty}=0\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>5</mn> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>x</mi> </mrow> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u221e</mi> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> </math></span> since <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_242\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\frac{5}{\\infty}\\cdot\\frac{x}{\\infty}=0\\cdot 0=0.\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <mrow> <mfrac> <mn>5</mn> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u221e</mi> </mfrac> <mo>\u22c5</mo> <mfrac> <mi>x</mi> <mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u221e</mi> </mfrac> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mrow> <mn>0</mn> <mo>\u22c5</mo> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> <mo>.</mo> </mrow> </math></span> Is this theoretical calculation correct or is there more to the concept than this?</p>",
  "Title": "Dividing Complex Numbers by Infinity",
